An Upper Area Court sitting in Kasuwan Nama in Jos, Plateau State on Thursday sentenced a 25-year-old trader, Abba Arando, to two years imprisonment for stealing carrots worth N65,000. The Judge, Lawal Suleiman, sentenced Arando after he pleaded guilty to trespass, mischief and theft. Suleiman, however, gave the convict an option to pay a fine of N20,000. The judge advised the convict to change his ways and not to engage in crimes. READ ALSO: Magistrate Orders Driver To Sweep Court Premises For Stealing Earlier, the prosecution counsel, Inspector Ibrahim Gokwat told the court that the case was reported at the Laranto Police Station, Jos on  September 5 by the complainant, Ahamad Mohammed. Gokwat said that the convict confessed that he trespassed and harvested carrots worth N65,000 from the complainantâ€™s farm without his consent. The offence, he said, contravened the provisions of sections 327, 312 and 271 of the Penal Code law. (NAN) The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) on Tuesday reported 176 new cases of COVID-19 infections in the country, taking the total number of cases to 55,632. The number of patients that have been discharged from hospital now stands at 43,610 while the number of recorded deaths is 1,070. At least 17 states reported new cases with the Federal Capital Territory (FCT) recording the highest number of cases. It had 40 new cases. Lagos State had the second highest number of new cases of COVID-19 with 34, while Plateau State had 26. In Enugu State, there were 14 new infections, 12 each in Delta and Ogun states, nine in Ondo State, eight in Oyo State, six in Ekiti State, four in Ebonyi State, two each in Adamawa, Nasarawa, Kwara and Rivers states, Edo, Osun and Bauchi states each had just one cases of new infection of the Coronavirus disease.